      <div xml:id="NA155-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu iraṇṭāṅ kūṭṭattut talaiviyai etirppaṭṭut (ETv: etirppaṭṭuk kūṭaluṟum) talaivaṉ colliyatu. 2. uṇarppuvayiṉ vārā ūṭaṟkaṇ talaivaṉ coṟṟatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what HE said when expecting HER for the second union. 2. It is also what HE said during a quarrel that had come up about union.(?)</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA155">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            oḷḷiḻai makaḷirō ṭōraiyu māṭāy</l>
<l>            vaḷḷitaḻ neytaṟ ṟoṭalaiyum puṉaiyāy</l>
<l>            viripūṅ kāṉa loruciṟai niṉṟō</l>
<l>            yārai yōniṟ ṟoḻutaṉam viṉavutuṅ</l>
<l>            kaṇṭōr taṇṭā nalattait teṇṭiraip </l>
<l>            peruṅkaṭaṟ parappi ṉamarntuṟai yaṇaṅkō</l>
<l>            viruṅkaḻi maruṅki ṉilaipeṟ ṟaṉaiyō</l>
<l>            colliṉi maṭantai yeṉṟaṉe ṉataṉetir</l>
<l>            muḷḷeyiṟṟu muṟuvalun tiṟantaṉa</l>
<l>            pallita ḻuṇkaṇum parantavāṟ paṉiyē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“You who do neither join in play with bright-jewelled women</l>
<l>nor fashion a garland of many-petalled blue waterlilies,</l>
<l>you who is posed on one side of the wide-flowered seashore-grove,</l>
<l>who [are] you?</l>
<l rend="indent3">Having paid obeisance to you<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">toḻutuṉam viṉavutum</term>: here the former form apparently has to be taken as a <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term> expressing anteriority. The difference to an absolutive in the same position can in these cases only be one of emphasis.</note> we want to ask you,</l>
<l>who have goodness unmeasured(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">taṇṭā</term>: thus the explanation of T.V.G. What is the precise impact of the verb?</note> by those who have seen [you]:</l>
<l>[are you] a torment<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṇaṅku</term> is to be seen here probably in one of the first clear occurrences of the meaning "frightening female deity". In any case this is probably a late poem, since the topos of HIS doubt about the human origin of HER is a component of the <term xml:lang="ta">kōvai</term> (and it occurs in one of the many speaker <term xml:lang="ta">sūtra</term>-s in the TP), but it is not a topos of the early poetry.</note> abiding permanently by the extension</l>
<l rend="indent4">of the great sea</l>
<l>or have you taken a station near the dark backwaters?</l>
<l>Speak now, girl.”</l>
<l rend="indent2">I said. In answer to that</l>
<l>[her] thorn-teeth opened in a smile</l>
<l>and [her] many-petalled kajal eyes spread dew indeed.</l>
        </lg>
